<dl id="n37005p"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n37" href="#n37005p">N37 (VI.B.28A)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n37all.htm#n37005p"> 5(p)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> tattled <small>Black</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n37005p"><li>FW 545.26 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/lexrB.htm#n37005p">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/l39rB.htm#n37005p">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n37005p">MS BL 47484b-484</ms> </li><li>JJA 59:251 <a name="rBd15" href="../../FF/fdra/rda.htm#rBd15">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rB/rBd15.htm#n37005p">Draft: III&sect;3B.15</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The Endowment oath prescribed that if the covenant not to reveal the details of the ceremony was broken, the apostate was to have his bowels torn out and trampled under foot, his throat cut from ear to ear, and his tongue ripped from his mouth. <font color="green">[However]</font> &hellip; there is no trustworthy record of bowels that were torn out &hellip; or tongues that were ripped from <mark>tattling</mark> mouths; and enough people did tell about the Endowment ceremonies to supply sufficient victims. <small> M.R. Werner, <a name="MRWB" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#MRWB"><cite title="source">Brigham Young</cite></a> (1925) 285</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
